Explain Collection vs Stream
1) Nature
* Collection: A data structure that stores elements in memory (e.g., List, Set, Map). Represents data at rest.
* Stream: A data processing pipeline that operates on elements from a source (like a collection). Represents data in motion.
2) Storage
* Collection: Physically stores elements; you can add, remove, or update data.
* Stream: Does not store elements; only processes them.
3) Mutability
* Collection: Mutable — elements can be added, removed, or updated.
* Stream: Immutable — operations produce new streams, source remains unchanged.
4) Operations
* Collection: CRUD operations (Create, Read, Update, Delete).
* Stream: Functional operations — map, filter, reduce, collect.

