CopyOnWriteArrayList — What & When to Use
Definition
A thread-safe list using a copy-on-write strategy:
* Every write (add/remove) → creates a new copy of the internal array.
* Reads are fast, lock-free, and use a snapshot.
* Iterators never throw ConcurrentModificationException.
How It Works
* Reads: Happen on a volatile snapshot → super fast.
* Writes: Lock, copy array, modify, replace reference.
* Iterators: Snapshot-based, fail-safe.
Best Use Case
* Read-heavy, rarely updated lists (e.g., listeners, app config lists).
* Avoid for large lists or frequent writes.

How Resize Happens in HashMap
HashMap resizes by doubling capacity when size exceeds capacity * loadFactor.
* Entries are redistributed.
* Since Java 8, rehashing uses a bitwise method (low/high bucket split).
* Maintains O(1) amortized performance.

Internal Working of ConcurrentHashMap
Key Concepts
* Thread-safe without locking the entire map.
* Uses CAS, bucket-level locking, and parallel resizing.
* Reads: Lock-free
* Writes: Lock only the bucket
* Much more scalable than Hashtable or synchronizedMap.

