✅ ArrayList vs LinkedList (When to use)
1. ArrayList
* Backed by dynamic array.
* Fast for search/get → O(1) for index-based access.
* Slow for insert/delete in the middle (shifting needed).
* Best when:
    * You need random access (get element by index).
    * Mostly doing read/search operations.
    * Example: E-commerce product catalog → where you frequently display/search items but rarely insert/delete.

2. LinkedList
* Backed by doubly linked list.
* Fast for insert/delete at beginning/middle → O(1) if you already have reference.
* Slow for search/get by index → O(n).
* Best when:
    * You frequently add/remove elements in middle/start.
    * Order matters and random access is not required.
    * Example: Music playlist/Queue system → where songs are frequently added/removed.

🔹 Simple Interview Punchline:
* Use ArrayList when reads/searches are more common.
* Use LinkedList when insertions/deletions are more frequent.

